arch:property.oc:show_val: This is a medium sized unit medium to medium-dark brown bone with about 5% burning. There are a few very white bones that look very fresh, however, most of the bone is medium brown. There is little digestion and no trample polish. Apart from the X finds (discussed below) the fragment size is average with most of the long bone fragments under 4cm. Taxa include caprid, cattle and equid bones. All body parts are represented for the sheep and goats and there is one complete left radius (X3). Cattle bone includes teeth and phalanges, and one complete right metacarpal (X6) with articulated 2+3 and 4th carpal. These X finds seem like the first of a series of commemorative(?) deposits that occur in the succeeding layers of midden. This material looks like midden rather than room fill. It is interesting that it was distinct from the laminated middens of the east mound. There was one piece of fossilized bone from an 05 sized animal. Flot smpl. 2, >4mm, 100% sorted, diagnostics only The flot sample is medium brown bone with about 10% burning at both high and low temperatures. There is a lot of digested bone and one very gnawed and digested astragalus. Some of the bones are rolled, but most of the material is relatively sharp. The diagnostics are all sheep/goat feet and teeth. The sample is coherent and consistent with the dry sieved material. Last Number = F.241
